So the things could be a bit too salty and the service could be a little rough, but the food really isn’t too bad and apparently fairly authentic according to my grandma who is from that region of China. Whenever we go, we always get family style so my review will be based off of those dishes. The Phoenix Wrap with chicken is the best, the others are mediocre. I love the lotus root with fish paste on it. Never too salty, lotus root nice and crunchy. The chicken and crab hotpot is flavorful, filled with chicken, crab, and shrimp. Most of the stuff have already been stir fried before so take it out quickly for the most tender meat. Get it with noodles and vegetables (+10 each but large portions). Ask for refills whenever it’s out. The large intestine is amazing — our favorite out of most Chinese restaurants. Crispy and sweet. It’s also my grandpa and grandma’s favorite and we went here so many times. Tons of memory with them, and I guess it’s especially since he passed away recently. I recommend, though I know the quality can be spotty.

The food is tasty, but extremely oily.  My party ordered ten dishes.  The Shundeck stir fry with meat and mixed vegetables dish was good.  The braised duck and braised squabs were not impressive.  May have tasted better if the cooking method/technique used was different.  The squabs look like they were pre-marinated and then flash fried.  The most disappointing was the sliced fish with tofu and parsley soup.  The soup tasted off, smell weird, and tofu was lukewarm.  I had such soup elsewhere and know how it is supposed to taste and this was lacking in every way.  Lastly, I hope they change or replace some of the chairs.  A few of the chairs at our table either had cracks on the wooden boards (and not by design intention) or was shaky.
